00:16:16,520 --> 00:16:20,480
- Child, what you talkin' about?
- Your pen pal said he's gonna
take you to Hawaii?

224
00:16:20,560 --> 00:16:23,000
He's stationed in Korea, girl.
It ain't that far to go.

225
00:16:23,080 --> 00:16:26,720
He said he gonna marry me
and have a big party there,
cause he know the owner.

226
00:16:26,800 --> 00:16:29,400
Oh, yeah?
You're so full of shit.

227
00:16:29,480 --> 00:16:32,040
- Did you tell him about
your other husband?
- Bitch, shut up.

228
00:16:32,120 --> 00:16:37,480
Meet... you... in...
Honolu...

229
00:16:39,080 --> 00:16:42,360
Is that two O's and two U's?

230
00:17:00,520 --> 00:17:04,840
- I'm right here for you, girl.
- Let's just finish the letter.

231
00:17:06,280 --> 00:17:08,520
Go on!

232
00:17:12,640 --> 00:17:14,040
- Sam, good morning.
- Good morning.

233
00:17:14,120 --> 00:17:16,600
Um, look, l-I've been
looking at this Liggett file.

234
00:17:16,680 --> 00:17:19,040
L-I'd like to go back and see if
I can get her to work with us.

235
00:17:19,120 --> 00:17:21,720
Oh. So now it's
a matter of pride, huh?

236
00:17:21,800 --> 00:17:25,120
No, no, no, I just... I think it's the only way
we're gonna get anything new.

237
00:17:25,200 --> 00:17:29,800
You're wasting your time, Rick.
You've got two dozen people
to reinterview for the update.

238
00:17:29,880 --> 00:17:31,720
But they're all gonna say
the same thing, no?

239
00:17:31,800 --> 00:17:33,920
You're not gonna get anything
out of Liggett.

240
00:17:34,000 --> 00:17:36,760
She's making her stand.
I've been through this before.

241
00:17:36,840 --> 00:17:38,520
Well, Sam, I'd at least
like to try.

242
00:17:38,600 --> 00:17:41,360
Of course you would.
Everyone does the first time.

243
00:17:41,440 --> 00:17:43,280
It's called
the rescuer syndrome.

244
00:17:43,360 --> 00:17:45,920
That's great. I'm on the job three days,
I got a syndrome.

245
00:17:46,000 --> 00:17:49,720
She won't deal with you. They served
her death warrant last night.

246
00:17:49,800 --> 00:17:51,840
Execution's in 30 days.

247
00:18:04,040 --> 00:18:07,000
- I got five more minutes.
- Visitor.

248
00:18:07,080 --> 00:18:10,200
- Today?
- Someone from Clemency.

249
00:18:10,280 --> 00:18:14,360
- Tell him I don't wanna see him.
- Hey, I'm not your social secretary.
Come on.

250
00:18:19,560 --> 00:18:21,400
You know you are.

251
00:18:25,960 --> 00:18:30,120
This is your last clemency report.
Open it up, take a look.

252
00:18:31,520 --> 00:18:34,360
No, huh? I'll do it for you.

253
00:18:34,440 --> 00:18:37,480
You just look at the cover page, okay?
That's all. Just the cover page.

254
00:18:42,400 --> 00:18:46,120
You see what it says under
"recommendation"? "Deny clemency."

255
00:18:46,200 --> 00:18:48,120
- I can read.
- Yeah? Well, that might as
well read "Let's kill her."

256
00:18:48,200 --> 00:18:51,320
Now, you know why it says that?
Because you ain't give 'em anything.

257
00:18:51,400 --> 00:18:55,480
- They had nothing to work with.
- How long you had this job?

258
00:18:55,560 --> 00:18:57,280
Four days.

259
00:18:57,360 --> 00:18:59,560
So basically,
you don't know jack shit.

260
00:18:59,640 --> 00:19:02,200
That's right. I don't know why you're not
a good candidate for clemency.

261
00:19:02,280 --> 00:19:05,080
Now, maybe if I had more experience
I'd just give up and write you off as well.

262
00:19:05,160 --> 00:19:07,880
You probably think you know
everything about me.

263
00:19:07,960 --> 00:19:10,200
I know what's in that file.

264
00:19:10,280 --> 00:19:12,360
Look, even if I get clemency...

265
00:19:12,440 --> 00:19:16,240
it means life in here with no parole,
and that's no life.

266
00:19:16,320 --> 00:19:19,000
I'm not beggin' for mercy
I'm not gonna get.

267
00:19:19,080 --> 00:19:21,600
You think I wanna die?
I do not wanna die. Okay?

268
00:19:21,680 --> 00:19:24,920
- Well...
- But if I do, it's gonna be on my terms.

269
00:19:25,000 --> 00:19:29,320
You got that? My terms.
That's all I got.

270
00:19:31,040 --> 00:19:33,000
Frances!

271
00:20:13,880 --> 00:20:17,280
They know how to harness Negroes
down south too, I hear.

272
00:20:17,360 --> 00:20:20,680
With a strap across their back.
Come on.

273
00:20:39,760 --> 00:20:42,480
Mmm. Hmm.

274
00:20:56,880 --> 00:20:59,760
Get out of my house. Get out
of here, you thievin' whore!

275
00:20:59,840 --> 00:21:02,160
Get out of my house, damn you!

276
00:21:02,240 --> 00:21:04,200
Hey! What the fu...

277
00:21:17,320 --> 00:21:19,160
Cindy!

278
00:21:27,720 --> 00:21:30,600
Reg? Reggie?

279
00:21:33,680 --> 00:21:35,240
Reg, you awake?

280
00:21:40,920 --> 00:21:44,520
Reg? Reg?

281
00:22:37,800 --> 00:22:42,120
Untamed youth with one thing on
their minds... Barq's Root Beer.

282
00:22:42,200 --> 00:22:44,120
I know that you were
involved in her appeals.

283
00:22:44,200 --> 00:22:46,200
That's right, and I assisted
Ed Duffy at the trial.

284
00:22:46,280 --> 00:22:48,200
Listen, maybe we should
talk later. I got a hearing.

285
00:22:48,280 --> 00:22:50,840
Just a minute. Is there anybody
else I should be talking to?

286
00:22:50,920 --> 00:22:54,560
Her only family's a kid brother. It's been
a defence nightmare from day one.

287
00:22:54,640 --> 00:22:57,720
- That's because of the brutality
of the crime.
- That, yeah.

288
00:22:57,800 --> 00:23:00,280
And we only had nine days
to prepare for trial.

289
00:23:00,360 --> 00:23:03,520
Well, now, the girl... she, in
fact, knew her in school, yes?

290
00:23:03,600 --> 00:23:07,440
Yeah. And the boy was the son of none
other than of William J. McGuire.

291
00:23:07,520 --> 00:23:09,400
McGuire? What, construction?

292
00:23:09,480 --> 00:23:12,080
- Yeah. Hey.
- Hi, Linda.
- Listen.

293
00:23:12,160 --> 00:23:15,600
McGuire wanted her to get the death
penalty, and he lobbied like hell for it.

294
00:23:15,680 --> 00:23:17,560
- Huh.
- Listen, she got a tough break.
- Is there...

295
00:23:17,640 --> 00:23:19,400
But it wasn't like she would've
ever gotten the sympathy vote.

296
00:23:19,480 --> 00:23:22,280
Is there anybody out there with
anything good to say about her?

297
00:23:24,040 --> 00:23:26,120
Nobody I'd let
baby-sit my child.

298
00:23:28,200 --> 00:23:31,280
- You again.
- Me again.

299
00:23:31,360 --> 00:23:35,160
- Well, it gets me away from the TVs.
- TVs?

300
00:23:35,240 --> 00:23:37,120
Well, they got those TVs
down in the pod...

301
00:23:37,200 --> 00:23:40,480
blastin' game shows
and soap operas all day long.

302
00:23:40,560 --> 00:23:43,840
That's what I'd call cruel
and unusual punishment.

303
00:23:43,920 --> 00:23:45,920
Yeah. No question.

304
00:23:46,000 --> 00:23:49,880
Guess they figure by the time they get
around to killin' you, you'll be grateful.

305
00:23:49,960 --> 00:23:53,600
Well, I'm just glad you consider me
a notch up from that kind of torture.

306
00:23:53,680 --> 00:23:55,560
Just a notch.

307
00:23:57,520 --> 00:24:00,200
What do you want?

308
00:24:00,280 --> 00:24:02,520
Well, let's start with
some names, okay?

309
00:24:02,600 --> 00:24:06,480
Anybody out there with anything
good to say about you?

310
00:24:06,560 --> 00:24:09,480
When I was out in the free world,
there wasn't anything good about me.

311
00:24:10,920 --> 00:24:14,560
- You could talk to Reggie.
- Oh? Who's Reggie?

312
00:24:14,640 --> 00:24:18,520
She's my cell neighbour.
She killed both her husbands.

313
00:24:18,600 --> 00:24:23,320
By the time they were about to arrest her,
she was just about to marry
number three.

314
00:24:23,400 --> 00:24:26,840
Well, she... she might not make
the best character witness, uh...

315
00:24:30,760 --> 00:24:33,080
- What about your brother?
- Billy?

316
00:24:33,160 --> 00:24:36,120
I know he thinks I hate him,
but I don't.

317
00:24:36,200 --> 00:24:39,960
I just wasn't a very good sister.
I was runnin' wild.

318
00:24:40,040 --> 00:24:43,720
- Is he still in St. Charles?
- Last I heard.

319
00:24:43,800 --> 00:24:46,280
He's almost 22.

320
00:24:46,360 --> 00:24:48,640
His birthday's in April.

321
00:24:48,720 --> 00:24:51,400
Were you close?

322
00:24:51,480 --> 00:24:53,920
Well, we had different fathers.

323
00:24:54,000 --> 00:24:56,760
Neither one of us knew 'em.

324
00:24:56,840 --> 00:24:59,400
After my mama died,
it was just us.

325
00:24:59,480 --> 00:25:02,120
Yeah, you were, uh, what, 16?

326
00:25:03,520 --> 00:25:06,760
Yeah. She died two days
after my 16th birthday.

327
00:25:08,720 --> 00:25:10,680
What was she like?

328
00:25:12,680 --> 00:25:14,960
Pretty. Wild.

329
00:25:16,560 --> 00:25:20,320
When she was feelin' good,
she could be a lot of fun.

330
00:25:20,400 --> 00:25:22,640
She wasn't like
anybody's mama I knew.

331
00:25:22,720 --> 00:25:26,080
We were more like sisters,
I guess.

332
00:25:26,160 --> 00:25:30,840
She just couldn't stay clean. I guess
she passed that on to me.

333
00:25:30,920 --> 00:25:33,320
Now, what is it
you're drawing there?

334
00:25:38,640 --> 00:25:41,680
Oh. Well, sorry I asked.

335
00:25:41,760 --> 00:25:44,480
It say in my file
I take drawing lessons?

336
00:25:44,560 --> 00:25:47,000
- No, I don't think so.
- I do.

337
00:25:47,080 --> 00:25:51,240
Through the mail.
Helps me pass the time.

338
00:25:51,320 --> 00:25:53,920
You know, and every week they
give you something new to draw.

339
00:25:54,000 --> 00:25:55,880
This week it's castles.

340
00:25:57,320 --> 00:25:59,160
Takes me away.

341
00:26:04,880 --> 00:26:07,720
Do you think you could get me
a picture of the Taj Mahal?

342
00:26:09,160 --> 00:26:13,000
- Yeah. Why?
- I wanna draw it.

343
00:26:13,080 --> 00:26:17,120
Taj Mahal? I expect that's
not too easy to draw.

344
00:26:17,200 --> 00:26:20,080
Well, I got 23 and a half hours
a day to get it right.

345
00:26:28,320 --> 00:26:30,560
No. No, hold our table.

346
00:26:30,640 --> 00:26:32,560
We are on our way.

347
00:26:32,640 --> 00:26:35,000
- Order a good bottle of red.
We'll be there in ten.
- No, Johnny, l...

348
00:26:35,080 --> 00:26:39,120
- The ladies are not happy.
- You gotta apologize for me, cause I gotta work tonight.
- Aw, come on.

349
00:26:39,200 --> 00:26:42,360
No, no, no, I been going through
the transcripts from the Liggett trial,
and listen to this...

350
00:26:42,440 --> 00:26:45,160
- Sam gave you Liggett?
- Yeah. He's got that guy Henry Reese.

351
00:26:45,240 --> 00:26:47,760
Well, Liggett shouldn't keep you that
busy. It's a pretty open-and-shut case.

352
00:26:47,840 --> 00:26:51,160
- No, no, not necessarily.
- Huh? Well, it always
seemed that way to me.

353
00:26:51,240 --> 00:26:52,760
- Yeah, but...
- And I'm familiar with the case.

354
00:26:52,840 --> 00:26:54,480
No. L-I found this
police report, right?

355
00:26:54,560 --> 00:26:57,240
Her brother said that she and her
codefendant had been up for two days...

356
00:26:57,320 --> 00:26:58,840
smoking crack
and robbing houses.

357
00:26:58,920 --> 00:27:01,480
At the sentencing hearing, her lawyer
doesn't say word one about drugs...

358
00:27:01,560 --> 00:27:03,960
or intoxication or even a possible
lack of premeditation.

359
00:27:04,040 --> 00:27:05,880
Well, that's a judgement call.

360
00:27:05,960 --> 00:27:08,600
Yeah, but when juries vote to execute,
the key issue is intent.

361
00:27:08,680 --> 00:27:12,360
I mean, was this murder intentional?
Was there a reasonable expectation
that death would result?

362
00:27:12,440 --> 00:27:14,360
I was a prosecutor.
I know the law.

363
00:27:14,440 --> 00:27:17,080
Well, then why didn't the lawyer use it?
'Cause this girl was blasted
out of her mind.

364
00:27:17,160 --> 00:27:19,000
It would've at least raised
a doubt with the jury.

365
00:27:19,080 --> 00:27:20,920
- Does it make it a clemency issue?
- No, not technically.

366
00:27:21,000 --> 00:27:23,400
Then stay within the guidelines
of your office and wrap this one up.

367
00:27:23,480 --> 00:27:26,000
Hold on. Does she have to die because
she had a lousy defence lawyer...

368
00:27:26,080 --> 00:27:27,920
and the father of one of her victims
is a buddy of the governor?

369
00:27:28,000 --> 00:27:30,800
No. She has to die because
she committed a double murder.

370
00:27:30,880 --> 00:27:33,000
Well, I'm not saying that she doesn't
deserve to be behind bars.

371
00:27:33,080 --> 00:27:36,960
I'm saying I don't think this woman
deserves to be put to death.

372
00:27:38,800 --> 00:27:40,880
Let's go. Come on.

373
00:27:40,960 --> 00:27:43,480
- Whoa.
- I want things to work out for you here.

374
00:27:43,560 --> 00:27:45,560
- What does that mean?
- It means be sensible.

375
00:27:45,640 --> 00:27:47,640
- Don't patronize me.
- Oh, not intended.

376
00:27:47,720 --> 00:27:50,680
- Oh, I see. I'm just supposed
to shut up and be grateful...
- No, not grateful. Successful.

377
00:27:50,760 --> 00:27:54,200
- And you're dead set on preventing it.
- Oh, boy, John, I really
appreciate your confidence.

378
00:27:54,280 --> 00:27:58,760
- I want you to have a chance.
- Oh, by putting me in a job
where no one expects anything.

379
00:27:58,840 --> 00:28:01,160
What have you done
to deserve anything more?

380
00:28:04,400 --> 00:28:06,280
I think I've lost my appetite.

381
00:28:22,480 --> 00:28:24,920
- Can you tell me where Morris lives?
- Next one.

382
00:28:37,240 --> 00:28:39,800
Hi.

383
00:28:39,880 --> 00:28:41,720
- Who are you?
- Uh, Miss Morris, well, I'm Rick Hayes.

384
00:28:41,800 --> 00:28:43,640
I'm with the State Clemency Board.

385
00:28:43,720 --> 00:28:46,720
- What's it about?
- Well, it's about your niece,
Cindy Liggett.

386
00:28:46,800 --> 00:28:49,080
- No.
- No, she's not your niece?

387
00:28:49,160 --> 00:28:51,000
- No. Not any more.
- Well, she did live here, yes?

388
00:28:51,080 --> 00:28:53,080
- Mm-mmm. No. No.
- Well, uh, can I just ask you...

389
00:28:53,160 --> 00:28:55,040
- There seems to be a...
- No.

390
00:29:01,680 --> 00:29:03,680
Ooh, baby, you drive me

391
00:29:03,760 --> 00:29:07,480
So don't send me home

392
00:29:07,560 --> 00:29:11,880
I dressed up my windows
and I shined up my chrome

393
00:29:13,480 --> 00:29:16,280
You're blowin'my gaskets

394
00:29:16,360 --> 00:29:19,760
Lay down a five and I'll
show you my kitty cat.

395
00:29:19,840 --> 00:29:23,240
Come here. I'd like to talk to you about
a girl named Cindy Liggett.

396
00:29:25,280 --> 00:29:29,800
Don't turn up my heater
Don't shut off my light

397
00:29:31,440 --> 00:29:34,200
How she got into it?

398
00:29:34,280 --> 00:29:36,120
How far back you want me to go?

399
00:29:36,200 --> 00:29:39,480
I mean, her mama's boyfriend
got her high on smack when she
was 14, and then he fucked her.

400
00:29:39,560 --> 00:29:43,000
- So...
- Cindy got into fuckin' and shootin' up
because that's what her mama was into.

401
00:29:43,080 --> 00:29:45,160
Tell me about
the girl she killed.

402
00:29:45,240 --> 00:29:47,320
- Debbie Hunt.
- Yeah. What, you knew her?

403
00:29:47,400 --> 00:29:51,000
Everybody knew Debbie.
Her daddy was foreman at McGuire.

404
00:29:51,080 --> 00:29:54,120
You... Cindy's mom, she worked at
McGuire Lumber as well, yeah?

405
00:29:54,200 --> 00:29:57,400
Hunt's bookkeeper. Hell, she couldn't
add water to orange juice.

406
00:29:57,480 --> 00:29:59,640
What, like personal favours?

407
00:29:59,720 --> 00:30:02,200
On-the-job services.

408
00:30:02,280 --> 00:30:04,640
Sweet deal for old Hunt
till rumours started flyin'.

409
00:30:04,720 --> 00:30:07,360
Then she spread it around she stole
from petty cash and fired her.

410
00:30:07,440 --> 00:30:11,240
I'm sorry. You're saying that she knew this
when she went in that house that night.

411
00:30:11,320 --> 00:30:14,120
It's like she was trying to
get even for her mom.

412
00:30:14,200 --> 00:30:16,960
She was too screwed up
to know what she was doin'.

413
00:30:17,040 --> 00:30:19,800
- I loved her and all, but...
- Did you see her that night?

414
00:30:19,880 --> 00:30:22,200
You know if she
was on any drugs?

415
00:30:23,400 --> 00:30:25,720
Look, I'm on next.

416
00:31:06,440 --> 00:31:11,000
Doug? Hi. I'm, I'm Rick Hayes.
I'm with the Clemency Board.

417
00:31:11,080 --> 00:31:15,000
The reason I'm here is, uh, it looks like
Cindy could be executed in three weeks.

418
00:31:15,080 --> 00:31:18,040
- Uh-huh.
- Well, l-I'm just...

419
00:31:18,120 --> 00:31:20,520
l-I'm wondering, uh,
now that it's ancient history...

420
00:31:20,600 --> 00:31:23,760
if there was anything you might
like to add before it's too late.

421
00:31:23,840 --> 00:31:26,960
- Like what?
- Well...

422
00:31:27,040 --> 00:31:30,120
Well, l-I know you plea-bargained
down to second-degree murder...

423
00:31:30,200 --> 00:31:33,080
- in exchange for testifying
against her at the trial...
- Yeah.

424
00:31:33,160 --> 00:31:35,960
And at the trial you said
the whole thing was her idea.

425
00:31:38,000 --> 00:31:41,760
- Actually, that's kind of unusual, isn't it?
- Why?

426
00:31:41,840 --> 00:31:44,800
I don't know. I mean,
17-year-old guys...

427
00:31:44,880 --> 00:31:48,160
don't usually let girls lead 'em
around, now, do they?

428
00:31:50,320 --> 00:31:53,280
Maybe she was the one
that was unusual.

429
00:31:53,360 --> 00:31:56,040
Th-The two of you had pulled off
quite a few burglaries that summer.

430
00:31:56,120 --> 00:32:00,320
- So she masterminded all of'em.
- I was 17 fuckin' years old, boy.

431
00:32:00,400 --> 00:32:03,880
Oh, uh, I see what you mean. She was...
She was older. She was, what, 19?

432
00:32:03,960 --> 00:32:06,440
Yeah, 19, goin' on about 30.

433
00:32:06,520 --> 00:32:08,600
And drugs. What kind of drugs
were you on?

434
00:32:08,680 --> 00:32:12,120
Some weed, some beer.

435
00:32:12,200 --> 00:32:14,560
- That's all?
- Yeah.

436
00:32:14,640 --> 00:32:16,560
What about crack?

437
00:32:16,640 --> 00:32:20,280
- Nah, no crack.
- You sure? Because the,
the police report...

438
00:32:20,360 --> 00:32:22,360
- Am I sure?
- Yeah.

439
00:32:22,440 --> 00:32:24,280
You think I'm ever gonna
forget that night?

440
00:32:24,360 --> 00:32:27,720
Well, you would if it would save you from
being executed, now, wouldn't you?

441
00:32:30,760 --> 00:32:33,800
- You're fuckin' with me.
- No, you help me, and maybe
I can help you.

442
00:32:33,880 --> 00:32:36,920
- Did she send you?
- No.

